    <h2>A. Terminology</h2>

    <h3>Epidemiology</h3>

    <p>
      Epidemiology is the study of epidemics or the increase,
      spread, and development of disease within a plant population.
      It also studies the different factors that influence disease
      occurrence and severity.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Studies disease spread</li>
        <li>Analyzes epidemic development</li>
        <li>Determines factors affecting outbreaks</li>
        <li>Helps predict and control epidemics</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Epidemic</h3>

    <p>
      An epidemic refers to any increase of disease within a plant
      population over a relatively large area and short period of time.
    </p>

    <h3>Epiphytotics</h3>

    <p>
      Epiphytotics refers specifically to epidemics of plant diseases.
    </p>

    <h3>Endemic Disease</h3>

    <p>
      An endemic disease is a disease naturally occurring or regularly
      found in a specific area or locality.
    </p>

    <h3>Exotic Disease</h3>

    <p>
      An exotic disease is a disease introduced from another region
      or country where it did not originally exist.
    </p>

    <h3>Pandemic Disease</h3>

    <p>
      A pandemic disease is a disease occurring over very large regions,
      countries, or continents.
    </p>

    <h3>Sporadic Disease</h3>

    <p>
      A sporadic disease occurs irregularly and unpredictably.
    </p>

    <h2>B. Elements of an Epidemic</h2>

    <p>
      Plant disease epidemics develop due to the timely combination
      of several important factors.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Susceptible host</li>
        <li>Virulent pathogen</li>
        <li>Favorable environment</li>
        <li>Intervention by man</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>1. Susceptible Host</h3>

    <p>
      The plant host must be vulnerable or lacking resistance to the
      pathogen for disease to occur.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Virulent Pathogen</h3>

    <p>
      The pathogen must possess the ability to infect and cause disease
      successfully.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Favorable Environment</h3>

    <p>
      Environmental conditions such as moisture, humidity, and temperature
      greatly influence disease development.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Intervention by Man</h3>

    <p>
      Human activities may help spread diseases through contaminated
      tools, infected planting materials, improper cultural practices,
      and movement of pathogens between areas.
    </p>

    <h2>C. Factors Affecting the Development of Epidemics</h2>

    <h3>1. Host Factors</h3>

    <h4>A. Genetic Resistance or Susceptibility</h4>

    <p>
      Plants with resistance genes are less likely to develop epidemics,
      while highly susceptible plants allow rapid disease spread.
    </p>

    <h4>B. Uniformity of Host Plants</h4>

    <p>
      Genetically uniform crops are more vulnerable because the pathogen
      can easily infect many plants with similar susceptibility.
    </p>

    <h4>C. Type of Crop</h4>

    <p>
      Annual crops such as rice, corn, and vegetables generally develop
      epidemics faster than perennial woody plants.
    </p>

    <h4>D. Age of Host Plants</h4>

    <p>
      Young plants are usually more susceptible to diseases than mature
      plants because their tissues are softer and less developed.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Pathogen Factors</h3>

    <h4>A. Level of Virulence</h4>

    <p>
      Highly virulent pathogens infect plants rapidly and produce larger
      amounts of inoculum.
    </p>

    <h4>B. Quantity of Inoculum</h4>

    <p>
      The greater the amount of inoculum near the host plant, the higher
      the chance of disease development.
    </p>

    <h4>C. Ecology of the Pathogen</h4>

    <p>
      The ability of pathogens to survive, reproduce, and adapt to
      environmental conditions affects epidemic development.
    </p>

    <h4>D. Mode of Spread</h4>

    <p>
      Airborne pathogens generally cause more epidemics because they
      disperse rapidly through wind currents.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Environmental Factors</h3>

    <h4>A. Moisture</h4>

    <p>
      Moisture favors spore germination, pathogen growth, and infection.
    </p>

    <h4>B. Temperature</h4>

    <p>
      Temperature influences pathogen reproduction, survival, and host
      susceptibility.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Human Factors</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Site selection and preparation</li>
      <li>Selection of propagative materials</li>
      <li>Cultural practices</li>
      <li>Disease control measures</li>
      <li>Introduction of new pathogens</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>D. Analysis of Epidemics</h2>

    <p>
      Disease increase over time depends on:
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Initial amount of disease or inoculum</li>
        <li>Rate of disease increase</li>
        <li>Duration of disease increase</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Compound Interest Diseases</h3>

    <p>
      Compound interest diseases involve repeated cycles of infection
      within one growing season. Pathogens continuously spread from
      plant to plant.
    </p>

    <p>
      These diseases increase rapidly because several generations of
      the pathogen are produced during the epidemic.
    </p>

    <h3>Simple Interest Diseases</h3>

    <p>
      Simple interest diseases involve only one major infection cycle
      during the growing season.
    </p>

    <p>
      Plant-to-plant spread is limited or absent after the primary cycle.
    </p>

    <h2>Van der Plank Concept</h2>

    <p>
      Van der Plank explained that epidemics usually begin with one
      infected plant and increase logarithmically under favorable
      conditions.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Disease starts slowly</li>
        <li>Rapid increase occurs during favorable conditions</li>
        <li>Disease eventually levels off</li>
        <li>Produces a sigmoid or S-shaped curve</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Zadoks and Schein (1979)</h2>

    <p>
      Zadoks and Schein described three major phases of epidemics.
    </p>

    <h3>1. Exponential or Logarithmic Phase</h3>

    <p>
      Disease increases rapidly due to abundant susceptible hosts.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Logistic Phase</h3>

    <p>
      Disease increase slows gradually as susceptible tissues decrease.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Terminal Phase</h3>

    <p>
      Disease development levels off because infection sites are exhausted
      or environmental conditions become unfavorable.
    </p>

